:C: MC(M_SUB_END)      = 99  MG(M_SUB_END)      =  0  MM(M_SUB_END)      = NO
*
*-----------------------------------------------------------------------
* CALC_END_OF_TAPE override
* Copied verbatim from MILL.LIB (the shared master library) - no changes
* to the logic itself. This override exists so :C: CALL(SETUP_SHEET_MILL),
* OUTPUT_ESTIMATED_TIME, and the native GETTOOLS(2,SYSTEM) tool table get
* appended into the main NC tape when SETUP_CONFIG<>0, instead of a
* separate .set file (see NO_SET_FILE/SETUP_CONFIG near the top of this
* file). A custom column-aligned tool table was attempted here directly in
* the post and went through six rounds of real compile errors and format
* bugs (see FrankenOKO_Post_Notes.md) - reverted back to this simple,
* proven-reliable native call. Tool-table formatting now happens downstream
* instead: either the setup-sheet-formatter ncSender plugin (cosmetic only),
* or - the better long-term answer - loading tools directly into ncSender's
* built-in Tool Library.
*-----------------------------------------------------------------------
*-----------------------------------------------------------------------
* CALC_START_OF_TAPE override
* Copied verbatim from MILL.LIB with one insertion: MAT_SCRATCH/
* THICK_SCRATCH copy lines placed immediately before CALL(START_OF_TAPE) -
* as late as possible before the header actually prints, since copying
* these too early (tried in CALC_POST_INITIALIZE previously) read a
* placeholder/partial value instead of the final CAM-resolved one.
*-----------------------------------------------------------------------
:SECTION=CALC_START_OF_TAPE
:C: LARGE_POT=8
:C: DEFINING_MACRO=NO
:C: OFFSET_RESIDENT=NO
:C: SEQ=1
:C: SEQ_INCREMENT=1
:C: MAX_SEQUENCE=99999
:C: PRELOAD_LAST=YES
:C: END_OF_TAPE_PRELOAD=NO
:C: INC_SUBPROGRAMS=NO
:C: LINE_AT_ANGLE=0
:C: CALC_CHANGE_TOOL=1
:C: GC(G_FPM)=94
:C: G_GROUP(GG(G_FPM))=GC(G_FPM)
:C: FIRST_Z_POS=0
:C: MAX_ARC_RADIUS=0
:C: CALL(CALC_INITIALIZE)
*
:C: GETTOOLS(2,CALC_PRELOAD_TOOL)
* NOTE: the native preload fixups (LAST_PRELOAD overwrite of TOOL_ARRAY(0)
* and the ARRAY_COUNT=1 reset) previously lived right here. They are now
* AFTER the tool table print below - they overwrite TOOL_ARRAY(0), which
* would corrupt the table's first row if they ran before it. The table
* must read the pristine preload data.
:C: IF SECTIONEXIST(DEBUG) THEN
:C: DEBUG=0 CALL(DEBUG)
:C: ENDIF
:C: IF PREDATOR_HEADER=1 THEN
:C:    IF SECTIONEXIST(START_PREDATOR_HEADER) THEN
:C:    CALL(START_PREDATOR_HEADER)
:C:    ENDIF
:C: GETTOOLS(1,CALC_PREDATOR_TOOLLIST)
:C:    IF SECTIONEXIST(END_PREDATOR_HEADER) THEN
:C:    CALL(END_PREDATOR_HEADER)
:C:    ENDIF
:C: ENDIF
:C: IF CAMWORKS_VER<CAM_REV2020 THEN GOTO8 ENDIF
:C: GET_SW_CUSTOM_PROP_BY_NAME({Material},CALC_GET_MATERIAL_CUSTOM_PROP)
:C8: THICK_SCRATCH=(thickness*25.4)
* MAT_SCRATCH is now populated via SolidWorks custom property retrieval
* (see CALC_GET_MATERIAL_CUSTOM_PROP below) instead of the CAMWorks TechDB
* "material" field - the TechDB field goes through this compiler's
* arithmetic expression evaluator, which mangles hyphens (confirmed via
* eight separate attempts); the SW custom property pipeline is a genuinely
* different mechanism (GET_SW_CUSTOM_PROP_BY_NAME/QUERY_SW_FIELD_VAL,
* already used elsewhere in MILL.LIB for SW document properties) that
* should not have the same issue, since it isn't evaluating an expression.
* Requires: a SolidWorks custom property literally named "Material" with
* the desired hyphenated value (confirmed present and working: evaluates
* to "6061-T6 (SS)").
* Stock Size in the header was tried and reverted - GET_SW_CUSTOM_PROP_
* BY_NAME cannot read anything from the Configuration Properties tab at
* all (confirmed via direct test: even a plain typed value there came
* back empty), and that's the only tab SolidWorks' auto-generated
* Bounding Box feature properties live in - so no automatic stock-size
* retrieval is possible with this compiler/SolidWorks combination. Not
* worth the manual-entry cost, so the line was removed rather than kept
* as a manual field.
* THICK_SCRATCH: 25.4mm = exactly 1 inch - same raw-inches storage pattern
* already found and fixed for tool diameter. No longer displayed in the
* header (Stock Size was tried and reverted, see above), left in place
* since OUTPUT_ESTIMATED_TIME and other sections may still reference
* THICKNESS_DISP elsewhere.
:C: IF SECTIONEXIST(START_OF_TAPE) THEN
:C: CALL(START_OF_TAPE)
:C: ENDIF
* Tool table moved here from CALC_END_OF_TAPE (per request: table under
* the header instead of at the end). At this moment the native arrays
* (TOOL_ARRAY/TOOL_DIAM_ARRAY/TOOL_TYPE_ARRAY/TOOL_COMM_ARRAY) hold pure,
* internally-consistent preload data - all written at matching indices by
* the native CALC_PRELOAD_TOOL loop. The end-of-tape corruption that
* forced the CORR_* array workaround came from runtime tool-change
* captures mixing into these arrays at shifted indices - that mixing
* hasn't happened yet at this point, so the native arrays are safe to
* read here (CALC_PRINT_TOOL_TABLE reads the native type/comm arrays,
* not CORR_*).
:C: IF SETUP_CONFIG<>0 THEN
:C:    IF SECTIONEXIST(OUTPUT_TOOL_LIST_HEADER) THEN
:C:    CALL(OUTPUT_TOOL_LIST_HEADER)
:C:    ENDIF
:C: CALL(CALC_PRINT_TOOL_TABLE)
:C: ENDIF
:C: CALL(START_OF_TAPE_MOTION)
* Native preload fixups, relocated from right after GETTOOLS (see note
* there) - must run before the first tool change (ARRAY_COUNT=1 is what
* the runtime capture indices are calibrated against) but after the
* table print (they overwrite TOOL_ARRAY(0)).
:C: IF LAST_PRELOAD<>0 THEN
:C:    IF LAST_PRELOAD<0 THEN
:C:    TOOL_ARRAY(0)=0
:C:    ELSE
:C:    TOOL_ARRAY(0)=LAST_PRELOAD
:C:    ENDIF
:C: ENDIF
:C: TOOL_ARRAY(ARRAY_COUNT)=TOOL_ARRAY(0)
:C: TOOL_DIAM_ARRAY(ARRAY_COUNT)=TOOL_DIAM_ARRAY(0)
:C: ARRAY_COUNT=1
*
:C: IF SECTIONEXIST(OUTPUT_SW_PROPERTY) THEN
:C: CALL(CALC_GET_SW_PROPERTIES)
:C: ENDIF
*
:SECTION=CALC_END_OF_TAPE
:C: IF SECTIONEXIST(DEBUG) THEN
:C: DEBUG=11 CALL(DEBUG)
:C: ENDIF
:C: CALL(CALC_TOTAL_TIME)
:C: CALL(CALC_REMOVE_OFFSET)
:C: IF SECTIONEXIST(RESET_X) THEN
:C:    IF SAVE_ANGLE_X<>0 THEN
:C:    CALL(RESET_X)
:C:    GOTO2
:C:    ENDIF
:C:    IF SAVE_ANGLE_Y<>0 THEN
:C:    CALL(RESET_Y)
:C:    GOTO2
:C:    ENDIF
:C:    IF SAVE_ANGLE_Z<>0 THEN
:C:    CALL(RESET_Z)
:C:    GOTO2
:C:    ENDIF
:C: ENDIF
:C2: IF SECTIONEXIST(END_OF_TAPE_PRELOAD) AND END_OF_TAPE_PRELOAD=YES THEN
:C:    IF TOOL<>TOOL_ARRAY(0) THEN
:C:    NEXT_TOOL=TOOL_ARRAY(0)
:C:    CALL(END_OF_TAPE_PRELOAD) ELSE
:C:    CALL(END_OF_TAPE)
:C:    ENDIF
:C: ELSE
:C: CALL(END_OF_TAPE)
:C: ENDIF
*
:C: IF SETUP_CONFIG<>0 THEN
:C:    IF OPR_AXIS_TYPE<2222 THEN
:C:    ADD_MACRO_START
:C:    ENDIF
:C: EOL={}
:C: SPACES(YES)
:C: CALL(SETUP_SHEET_MILL)
:C:    IF SECTIONEXIST(OUTPUT_ESTIMATED_TIME) THEN
:C:    CALL(OUTPUT_ESTIMATED_TIME)
:C:    ENDIF
* PROGRAM_END_BANNER (which embeds the Estimated Machine Time line) MUST
* be called from this exact position - inside this ADD_MACRO block, right
* after SETUP_SHEET_MILL. Calling it at the very end of CALC_END_OF_TAPE
* (after ADD_MACRO_END) printed the banner fine but with TIME values
* zeroed - confirmed by real output. The OUTPUT_ESTIMATED_TIME guard
* above is a harmless no-op (that section was removed; the time line
* lives inside the banner now).
* Prefer CAMWorks' own machining-time estimate (CW_TIME_*, computed by
* the CAM simulation engine - includes rapids, tool changes, etc.) over
* the post compiler's crude internal accumulator (CALC_TIME-derived
* TIME_*, which only tallies feed-move distance/feedrate and badly
* undercounts real multi-tool jobs). This mirrors the native
* CALC_SETUP_SHEET logic in MILL.LIB (~8603) which does exactly this
* swap before printing. Both sets were already computed by
* CALC_TOTAL_TIME at the top of this section.
:C:    IF CW_TIME<>0 THEN
:C:    TIME_HOURS=CW_TIME_HOURS
:C:    TIME_MINUTES=CW_TIME_MINUTES
:C:    TIME_SECONDS=CW_TIME_SECONDS
:C:    ENDIF
:C: CALL(PROGRAM_END_BANNER)
* Tool table no longer printed here - moved to CALC_START_OF_TAPE (under
* the header, per request). See CALC_PRINT_TOOL_TABLE.
:C:    IF OPR_AXIS_TYPE<2222 THEN
:C:    ADD_MACRO_END
:C:    ENDIF
:C: ENDIF
:C: IF SECTIONEXIST(PERCENT) THEN
:C:    IF OPR_AXIS_TYPE<2222 THEN
:C:    ADD_MACRO_START
:C:    ENDIF
:C: CALL(PERCENT)
:C:    IF OPR_AXIS_TYPE<2222 THEN
:C:    ADD_MACRO_END
:C:    ENDIF
:C: ENDIF
*
* Closing banner - called from inside the ADD_MACRO block above (see the
* comment there for why the position matters for the TIME values).
:SECTION=PROGRAM_END_BANNER
:T:;<EOL>
:T:; ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<EOL>
:T:; ###########################################################################<EOL>
:T:;     PROGRAM END<EOL>
:T:;        Estimated Machine Time: <TIME_HOURS> Hours, <TIME_MINUTES> Minutes and <TIME_SECONDS> Seconds<EOL>
:T:; ###########################################################################<EOL>
:T:; ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<EOL>
*
* Tool table print loop - now called from CALC_START_OF_TAPE (was inline
* here at end of tape). Reads the NATIVE type/comm arrays because at
* start-of-tape they hold pure preload data at consistent indices (the
* CORR_* workaround arrays exist for the end-of-tape case where runtime
* captures had contaminated the native arrays - see CALC_BEF_SETON_CODES;
* those captures are retained but currently unused by the table).
:SECTION=CALC_PRINT_TOOL_TABLE
:C: LOOP=0
:C1: TOOL=TOOL_ARRAY(LOOP)
* De-duplication: some tools get reloaded multiple times in a job (e.g.
* returning to an earlier tool after using a different one in between).
* The native tool array appends a new entry every time a tool is loaded,
* even if that exact tool number already has an entry - and the repeat
* entries were showing mismatched/Unknown data rather than that tool's
* real info. Fix: scan all EARLIER array positions before this one: if
* this tool number already appeared, skip printing it again entirely.
:C: IS_DUPLICATE=0
:C: SCAN_I=0
:C20: IF SCAN_I<LOOP THEN
:C:    IF TOOL_ARRAY(SCAN_I)=TOOL THEN IS_DUPLICATE=1 ENDIF
:C:    SCAN_I=(SCAN_I+1)
:C:    GOTO20
:C: ENDIF
:C: IF SETUP_CONFIG<>0 AND IS_DUPLICATE=0 THEN
:C: CUR_DIAM=(TOOL_DIAM_ARRAY(LOOP)*25.4)
:C: CUR_TYPE=TOOL_TYPE_ARRAY(LOOP)
:C: CUR_COMM=TOOL_COMM_ARRAY(LOOP)
* Unconditional *25.4 conversion (metric-only post) - TOOL_DIAM_ARRAY stores
* raw inches, unlike X/Y/Z position registers which auto-convert.
:C: IF CUR_TYPE=201 THEN
:C:    CALL(TOOL_ROW_TYPE_201)
:C: ELSE
:C:    IF CUR_TYPE=202 THEN
:C:       CALL(TOOL_ROW_TYPE_202)
:C:    ELSE
:C:       IF CUR_TYPE=203 THEN
:C:          CALL(TOOL_ROW_TYPE_203)
:C:       ELSE
:C:          IF CUR_TYPE=221 THEN
:C:             CALL(TOOL_ROW_TYPE_221)
:C:          ELSE
:C:             IF CUR_TYPE=222 THEN
:C:                CALL(TOOL_ROW_TYPE_222)
:C:             ELSE
:C:                IF CUR_TYPE=223 THEN
:C:                   CALL(TOOL_ROW_TYPE_223)
:C:                ELSE
:C:                   IF CUR_TYPE=204 THEN
:C:                      CALL(TOOL_ROW_TYPE_204)
:C:                   ELSE
:C:                      IF CUR_TYPE=205 THEN
:C:                         CALL(TOOL_ROW_TYPE_205)
:C:                      ELSE
:C:                         IF CUR_TYPE=206 THEN
:C:                            CALL(TOOL_ROW_TYPE_206)
:C:                         ELSE
:C:                            IF CUR_TYPE=207 THEN
:C:                               CALL(TOOL_ROW_TYPE_207)
:C:                            ELSE
:C:                               IF CUR_TYPE=208 THEN
:C:                                  CALL(TOOL_ROW_TYPE_208)
:C:                               ELSE
:C:                                  IF CUR_TYPE=209 THEN
:C:                                     CALL(TOOL_ROW_TYPE_209)
:C:                                  ELSE
:C:                                     IF CUR_TYPE=210 THEN
:C:                                        CALL(TOOL_ROW_TYPE_210)
:C:                                     ELSE
:C:                                        IF CUR_TYPE=211 THEN
:C:                                           CALL(TOOL_ROW_TYPE_211)
:C:                                        ELSE
:C:                                           IF CUR_TYPE=212 THEN
:C:                                              CALL(TOOL_ROW_TYPE_212)
:C:                                           ELSE
:C:                                              IF CUR_TYPE=213 THEN
:C:                                                 CALL(TOOL_ROW_TYPE_213)
:C:                                              ELSE
:C:                                                 IF CUR_TYPE=214 THEN
:C:                                                    CALL(TOOL_ROW_TYPE_214)
:C:                                                 ELSE
:C:                                                    IF CUR_TYPE=216 THEN
:C:                                                       CALL(TOOL_ROW_TYPE_216)
:C:                                                    ELSE
:C:                                                       IF CUR_TYPE=217 THEN
:C:                                                          CALL(TOOL_ROW_TYPE_217)
:C:                                                       ELSE
:C:                                                          IF CUR_TYPE=215 THEN
:C:                                                             CALL(TOOL_ROW_TYPE_215)
:C:                                                          ELSE
:C:                                                             IF CUR_TYPE=218 THEN
:C:                                                                CALL(TOOL_ROW_TYPE_218)
:C:                                                             ELSE
:C:                                                                CALL(TOOL_ROW_FALLBACK)
:C:                                                             ENDIF
:C:                                                          ENDIF
:C:                                                       ENDIF
:C:                                                    ENDIF
:C:                                                 ENDIF
:C:                                              ENDIF
:C:                                           ENDIF
:C:                                        ENDIF
:C:                                     ENDIF
:C:                                  ENDIF
:C:                               ENDIF
:C:                            ENDIF
:C:                         ENDIF
:C:                      ENDIF
:C:                   ENDIF
:C:                ENDIF
:C:             ENDIF
:C:          ENDIF
:C:       ENDIF
:C:    ENDIF
:C: ENDIF
:C: ENDIF
:C: LOOP=(LOOP+1)
:C: IF TOOL_ARRAY(LOOP)=(-1) OR TOOL_ARRAY(LOOP)=0 THEN
:C:    IF SECTIONEXIST(TOOL_LIST_FOOTER) THEN
:C:    CALL(TOOL_LIST_FOOTER)
:C:    ENDIF
:C: RETURN
:C: ENDIF
:C: GOTO1
*
:SECTION=CALC_GET_MATERIAL_CUSTOM_PROP
* Callback for GET_SW_CUSTOM_PROP_BY_NAME - copies the fetched SolidWorks
* custom property value (in QUERY_SW_FIELD_VAL, populated by the fetch
* call) into MAT_SCRATCH for display. If the property wasn't found,
* QUERY_SW_FIELD_VAL is empty and MAT_SCRATCH just stays empty too -
* matches the existing SECTIONEXIST(OUTPUT_SW_PROPERTY) guard pattern
* MILL.LIB itself uses for this same callback mechanism.
:C: IF QUERY_SW_FIELD_VAL={} THEN RETURN ENDIF
:C: MAT_SCRATCH=QUERY_SW_FIELD_VAL
*
:SECTION=CALC_TOOL_LIST_NOOP
* Empty callback for GETTOOLS - lets it refresh the tool arrays without
* triggering native table printing (only "SYSTEM" as 2nd arg does that).
:C: RETURN
*
:SECTION=OUTPUT_TOOL_LIST_HEADER
:T:; ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<EOL>
:T:;     TOOL TABLE<EOL>
:T:; ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<EOL>
:T:;  TOOL#     TOOL TYPE     DIAMETER   DESCRIPTION<EOL>
:T:; -------  --------------  --------   ------------------------------<EOL>
*
*
:SECTION=TOOL_ROW_TYPE_201
:T:;   <TOOL_NUM_DISP>       ENDMILL       <TOOL_DIAM_DISP>    <TOOL_COMM_DISP>  <EOL>
*
:SECTION=TOOL_ROW_TYPE_202
:T:;   <TOOL_NUM_DISP>       BALLNOSE      <TOOL_DIAM_DISP>    <TOOL_COMM_DISP>  <EOL>
*
:SECTION=TOOL_ROW_TYPE_203
:T:;   <TOOL_NUM_DISP>       HOGNOSE       <TOOL_DIAM_DISP>    <TOOL_COMM_DISP>  <EOL>
*
:SECTION=TOOL_ROW_TYPE_221
:T:;   <TOOL_NUM_DISP>     TAP ENDMILL     <TOOL_DIAM_DISP>    <TOOL_COMM_DISP>  <EOL>
*
:SECTION=TOOL_ROW_TYPE_222
:T:;   <TOOL_NUM_DISP>     TAP BALLNOSE    <TOOL_DIAM_DISP>    <TOOL_COMM_DISP>  <EOL>
*
:SECTION=TOOL_ROW_TYPE_223
:T:;   <TOOL_NUM_DISP>     TAP HOGNOSE     <TOOL_DIAM_DISP>    <TOOL_COMM_DISP>  <EOL>
*
:SECTION=TOOL_ROW_TYPE_204
:T:;   <TOOL_NUM_DISP>        DRILL        <TOOL_DIAM_DISP>    <TOOL_COMM_DISP>  <EOL>
*
:SECTION=TOOL_ROW_TYPE_205
:T:;   <TOOL_NUM_DISP>         BORE        <TOOL_DIAM_DISP>    <TOOL_COMM_DISP>  <EOL>
*
:SECTION=TOOL_ROW_TYPE_206
:T:;   <TOOL_NUM_DISP>         REAM        <TOOL_DIAM_DISP>    <TOOL_COMM_DISP>  <EOL>
*
:SECTION=TOOL_ROW_TYPE_207
:T:;   <TOOL_NUM_DISP>         TAP         <TOOL_DIAM_DISP>    <TOOL_COMM_DISP>  <EOL>
*
:SECTION=TOOL_ROW_TYPE_208
:T:;   <TOOL_NUM_DISP>     CENTER DRILL    <TOOL_DIAM_DISP>    <TOOL_COMM_DISP>  <EOL>
*
:SECTION=TOOL_ROW_TYPE_209
:T:;   <TOOL_NUM_DISP>     CORNER ROUND    <TOOL_DIAM_DISP>    <TOOL_COMM_DISP>  <EOL>
*
:SECTION=TOOL_ROW_TYPE_210
:T:;   <TOOL_NUM_DISP>     COUNTERSINK     <TOOL_DIAM_DISP>    <TOOL_COMM_DISP>  <EOL>
*
:SECTION=TOOL_ROW_TYPE_211
:T:;   <TOOL_NUM_DISP>     THREAD MILL     <TOOL_DIAM_DISP>    <TOOL_COMM_DISP>  <EOL>
*
:SECTION=TOOL_ROW_TYPE_212
:T:;   <TOOL_NUM_DISP>     THREAD MILL     <TOOL_DIAM_DISP>    <TOOL_COMM_DISP>  <EOL>
*
:SECTION=TOOL_ROW_TYPE_213
:T:;   <TOOL_NUM_DISP>       DOVETAIL      <TOOL_DIAM_DISP>    <TOOL_COMM_DISP>  <EOL>
*
:SECTION=TOOL_ROW_TYPE_214
:T:;   <TOOL_NUM_DISP>        KEYWAY       <TOOL_DIAM_DISP>    <TOOL_COMM_DISP>  <EOL>
*
:SECTION=TOOL_ROW_TYPE_216
:T:;   <TOOL_NUM_DISP>       LOLLIPOP      <TOOL_DIAM_DISP>    <TOOL_COMM_DISP>  <EOL>
*
:SECTION=TOOL_ROW_TYPE_217
:T:;   <TOOL_NUM_DISP>       FACEMILL      <TOOL_DIAM_DISP>    <TOOL_COMM_DISP>  <EOL>
*
:SECTION=TOOL_ROW_TYPE_215
:T:;   <TOOL_NUM_DISP>       UNKNOWN       <TOOL_DIAM_DISP>    <TOOL_COMM_DISP>  <EOL>
*
:SECTION=TOOL_ROW_TYPE_218
:T:;   <TOOL_NUM_DISP>       UNKNOWN       <TOOL_DIAM_DISP>    <TOOL_COMM_DISP>  <EOL>
*
:SECTION=TOOL_ROW_FALLBACK
:T:;   <TOOL_NUM_DISP>       UNKNOWN       <TOOL_DIAM_DISP>    <TOOL_COMM_DISP>  <EOL>
*

:SECTION=CALC_AFT_SETON_CODES
* Reverted - tried capturing TOOL_TYPE/TOOL_COMMENT here, but real test
* results showed this timing is too late (values here appear stale,
* showing the PREVIOUS tool's data). Moved the capture to
* CALC_BEF_SETON_CODES instead, matching the exact timing already proven
* correct by the tool-change header (which reads the same variables at
* that earlier point and is always correct). Left this section as a plain
* stub, matching the native default.
:C: RETURN
*
:SECTION=CALC_TOOL_CHANGE_HEADER
* Dispatches to one of 21 type-specific sections (matching the same proven
* pattern already used for the tool table), each printing the full
* 3-line tool-change header with the type name as literal text - no
* string-literal assignment exists in this compiler, confirmed repeatedly
* this session, so section-calling is the only safe way to get type-
* specific text into output.
:C: IF TOOL_TYPE=201 THEN
:C:    CALL(TOOL_CHANGE_HDR_TYPE_201)
:C: ELSE
:C:    IF TOOL_TYPE=202 THEN
:C:       CALL(TOOL_CHANGE_HDR_TYPE_202)
:C:    ELSE
:C:       IF TOOL_TYPE=203 THEN
:C:          CALL(TOOL_CHANGE_HDR_TYPE_203)
:C:       ELSE
:C:          IF TOOL_TYPE=221 THEN
:C:             CALL(TOOL_CHANGE_HDR_TYPE_221)
:C:          ELSE
:C:             IF TOOL_TYPE=222 THEN
:C:                CALL(TOOL_CHANGE_HDR_TYPE_222)
:C:             ELSE
:C:                IF TOOL_TYPE=223 THEN
:C:                   CALL(TOOL_CHANGE_HDR_TYPE_223)
:C:                ELSE
:C:                   IF TOOL_TYPE=204 THEN
:C:                      CALL(TOOL_CHANGE_HDR_TYPE_204)
:C:                   ELSE
:C:                      IF TOOL_TYPE=205 THEN
:C:                         CALL(TOOL_CHANGE_HDR_TYPE_205)
:C:                      ELSE
:C:                         IF TOOL_TYPE=206 THEN
:C:                            CALL(TOOL_CHANGE_HDR_TYPE_206)
:C:                         ELSE
:C:                            IF TOOL_TYPE=207 THEN
:C:                               CALL(TOOL_CHANGE_HDR_TYPE_207)
:C:                            ELSE
:C:                               IF TOOL_TYPE=208 THEN
:C:                                  CALL(TOOL_CHANGE_HDR_TYPE_208)
:C:                               ELSE
:C:                                  IF TOOL_TYPE=209 THEN
:C:                                     CALL(TOOL_CHANGE_HDR_TYPE_209)
:C:                                  ELSE
:C:                                     IF TOOL_TYPE=210 THEN
:C:                                        CALL(TOOL_CHANGE_HDR_TYPE_210)
:C:                                     ELSE
:C:                                        IF TOOL_TYPE=211 THEN
:C:                                           CALL(TOOL_CHANGE_HDR_TYPE_211)
:C:                                        ELSE
:C:                                           IF TOOL_TYPE=212 THEN
:C:                                              CALL(TOOL_CHANGE_HDR_TYPE_212)
:C:                                           ELSE
:C:                                              IF TOOL_TYPE=213 THEN
:C:                                                 CALL(TOOL_CHANGE_HDR_TYPE_213)
:C:                                              ELSE
:C:                                                 IF TOOL_TYPE=214 THEN
:C:                                                    CALL(TOOL_CHANGE_HDR_TYPE_214)
:C:                                                 ELSE
:C:                                                    IF TOOL_TYPE=216 THEN
:C:                                                       CALL(TOOL_CHANGE_HDR_TYPE_216)
:C:                                                    ELSE
:C:                                                       IF TOOL_TYPE=217 THEN
:C:                                                          CALL(TOOL_CHANGE_HDR_TYPE_217)
:C:                                                       ELSE
:C:                                                          IF TOOL_TYPE=215 THEN
:C:                                                             CALL(TOOL_CHANGE_HDR_TYPE_215)
:C:                                                          ELSE
:C:                                                             IF TOOL_TYPE=218 THEN
:C:                                                                CALL(TOOL_CHANGE_HDR_TYPE_218)
:C:                                                             ELSE
:C:                                                                CALL(TOOL_CHANGE_HDR_FALLBACK)
:C:                                                             ENDIF
:C:                                                          ENDIF
:C:                                                       ENDIF
:C:                                                    ENDIF
:C:                                                 ENDIF
:C:                                              ENDIF
:C:                                           ENDIF
:C:                                        ENDIF
:C:                                     ENDIF
:C:                                  ENDIF
:C:                               ENDIF
:C:                            ENDIF
:C:                         ENDIF
:C:                      ENDIF
:C:                   ENDIF
:C:                ENDIF
:C:             ENDIF
:C:          ENDIF
:C:       ENDIF
:C:    ENDIF
:C: ENDIF
*
:SECTION=CALC_BEF_SETON_CODES
* Overriding this empty, designed-for-customization stub (native default
* is just RETURN) - called at the very start of CALC_SUB_TOOL_CHANGE_MILL,
* before anything else, including the coolant-off SETON and the eventual
* call to SUB_TOOL_CHANGE_MILL. Safe, minimal-footprint hook - doesn't
* touch or duplicate any of that large wrapper's own logic.
* Also captures TOOL_TYPE/TOOL_COMMENT here now (moved from
* CALC_AFT_SETON_CODES, which proved unreliable - see that section's notes)
* - this exact timing is already proven correct, since the tool-change
* header reads the same two variables at this same point and is always
* right.
* Writes into CORR_TYPE_ARRAY/CORR_COMM_ARRAY (our own dedicated arrays),
* NOT the native TOOL_TYPE_ARRAY/TOOL_COMM_ARRAY - MILL.LIB's own
* CALC_PRELOAD_TOOL (fired once via GETTOOLS(2,...) at the very start of
* the tape) also writes those two native arrays, and its leftover data
* was never cleared the way TOOL_ARRAY(0)/TOOL_DIAM_ARRAY(0) explicitly
* are - separate array names sidestep that collision entirely.
* INDEX: diagnostic logging (removed after confirming, see
* FrankenOKO_Post_Notes.md) proved that TOOL_ARRAY ends up storing each
* tool at exactly ARRAY_COUNT-1 relative to what this hook sees, not
* ARRAY_COUNT itself as originally assumed - confirmed as a clean,
* constant 1-index offset across all 25 tool loads in a real test job.
* Something between this hook and the native TOOL_ARRAY write advances
* ARRAY_COUNT once more than expected; rather than continue chasing that
* inside compiled/native code we can't inspect, we compensate directly.
:C: CORR_TYPE_ARRAY(ARRAY_COUNT-1)=TOOL_TYPE
:C: CORR_COMM_ARRAY(ARRAY_COUNT-1)=TOOL_COMMENT
:C: CALL(CALC_TOOL_CHANGE_HEADER)
:C: RETURN
*
:SECTION=TOOL_CHANGE_HDR_TYPE_201
:T:; ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<EOL>
:T:;    Tool Change<EOL>
:T:;        Tool #<TOOL_NUM_RAW_DISP>: ENDMILL <TOOL_COMMENT_DISP><EOL>
:T:; ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<EOL>
*
:SECTION=TOOL_CHANGE_HDR_TYPE_202
:T:; ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<EOL>
:T:;    Tool Change<EOL>
:T:;        Tool #<TOOL_NUM_RAW_DISP>: BALLNOSE <TOOL_COMMENT_DISP><EOL>
:T:; ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<EOL>
*
:SECTION=TOOL_CHANGE_HDR_TYPE_203
:T:; ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<EOL>
:T:;    Tool Change<EOL>
:T:;        Tool #<TOOL_NUM_RAW_DISP>: HOGNOSE <TOOL_COMMENT_DISP><EOL>
:T:; ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~<EOL>
*
